  ],
  "text": "The LLVM SelectionDAG type legalization assertion failure 'Cannot expand this type; LLVM lacks the right hooks' traces to the core type legalization infrastructure in the SelectionDAG package.\n\n## Key Files and Components:\n\n1. **Type Legalization Orchestrator**: The `DAGTypeLegalizer` class defined in `llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/LegalizeTypes.h` (line 31) orchestrates the overall type legalization process. This class manages the transformation of illegal value types into legal ones through multiple legalization strategies (promotion, expansion, splitting, widening, etc.).\n\n2. **Main Entry Point and Framework**: `llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/LegalizeTypes.cpp` contains the core legalization loop in the `DAGTypeLegalizer::run()` method. This file implements the main legalization algorithm that walks the DAG and applies appropriate transformations based on type actions returned by the target lowering interface.\n\n3. **Type Expansion for Integers**: The `ExpandIntegerResult` function in `llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/LegalizeIntegerTypes.cpp` (starting at line 3024) handles expansion of illegal integer result types. When encountering an unsupported operation, it reports the fatal error 'Do not know how to expand the result of this operator!' (line 3039-3040), which corresponds to the assertion about lacking the right hooks.\n\n4. **Type Expansion for Floating-Point**: The `ExpandFloatResult` function in `llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/LegalizeFloatTypes.cpp` (line 1567) similarly handles expansion of illegal floating-point result types, with error handling at line 1582.\n\n5. **EVT (Extended Value Type) Definition**: The EVT structure is defined in `llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/ValueTypes.h` (line 35). The `isSimple()` method at line 137 checks whether a value type is simple (backed by a MVT) or extended. This method is critical in determining how types are processed during legalization.\n\n6. **Operation Legalization**: The `SelectionDAGLegalize` class in `llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/LegalizeDAG.cpp` (line 88) handles legalization of operations (as opposed to types). It works in conjunction with DAGTypeLegalizer to ensure all node operations and types conform to the target's capabilities.\n\n## Error Source:\n\nThe error manifests when the type legalization framework encounters a value type that:\n- Has an illegal type that requires expansion\n- But the specific node operation lacks an expansion handler in the corresponding Legalize*Types.cpp file (LegalizeIntegerTypes, LegalizeFloatTypes, etc.)\n\nThis occurs in the switch statements of functions like `ExpandIntegerResult` (line 3033 in LegalizeIntegerTypes.cpp), where if no matching case handles the operation opcode, the default case triggers the fatal error, indicating that LLVM lacks the 'right hooks' (handlers/cases) to expand that particular operation for the illegal type."
}

